               <p>THOMAS FREVILLION. I <rs id="t18300415-200-viclabel1116" type="occupation">keep the <placeName id="t18300415-200-crimeloc1117">Rum Puncheon in Old-street</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-crimeloc1117" type="placeName" value="Rum Puncheon in Old-street"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-crimeloc1117" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-200-off1114 t18300415-200-crimeloc1117"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-200-victim1781 t18300415-200-viclabel1116"></join>. On the 3rd of April, about one o'clock, a person came in and had a glass of ale and a biscuit; he went out, and bade me good morning - I went into the parlour to get the glass, and missed a looking-glass, which had been fastened over the mantel-piece, and the window was open; I went after the man who had just left the house, as I thought he had handed it to some other person; it must have been taken out of the window- I found the prisoner in Bath-street with the glass, within five minutes after the other man had left my house- he ran away, but I never lost sight of him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-200-person1782">
                  JOSEPH 
                  NEWMAN
               <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1782" type="surname" value="NEWMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1782" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1782" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a bricklayer. I heard the cry of Stop thief! and saw the prosecutor pursuing the prisoner - I took him; the prosecutor had taken the glass from him, put it down, and pursued him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-200-person1783">
                  JOHN 
                  GLIBBERY
               <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1783" type="surname" value="GLIBBERY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1783" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1783" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner - he said distress drove him to it, and he wished to be transported.</p>
               <p>COURT to 
               <persName id="t18300415-200-person1784">
                  THOMAS 
                  FREVILLION
               <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1784" type="surname" value="FREVILLION"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1784" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-person1784" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. When you took the glass from him, did you lose sight of him? A. No, not at all - there was no other way it could go but out of the window.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, stating that he met a gentleman, who employed him to go to the prosecutor's house, and that the gentleman went in and gave him the glass out at the window, to take to the Eagle-tavern, City-road - he had told the officer he wished to be transported, because he was in distressed circumstances.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300415-200-verdict1118" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-200-verdict1118" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
